04882nam a22006615i 9781478023753DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780237537 a10.1515/97814780237532doi  a(DE-B1597)642222  a(OCoLC)1343899103  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aEDU0150002bisacsh04a378.756/563223//eng/20220706eng1 aBliwise, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Pivot :bOne Pandemic, One University /cRobert J. Bliwise. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: The Course of a Pandemic -- t1 The Campus as a Physical Space -- t2 The Campus as a Space for Learning -- t3 The Campus as a Space for Discovery -- t4 The Campus as a Space for Collective Well-Being -- t5 The Campus as a Space for Individual Well-Being -- t6 The Campus as a Space for Personal Growth -- t7 The Campus as a Space for Renewal -- t8 The Campus as a Space Where Societal Issues Play Out -- t9 The Campus as a Space for Improving the Human Condition -- t10 The Campus Reaffirmed0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe COVID-19 pandemic presented higher education with an unprecedented challenge: How could institutions continue the basic work of teaching and research while maintaining safe environments for their faculty, staff, and students? In The Pivot, Robert J. Bliwise traces Duke University’s response to the pandemic to show how higher education broadly met that challenge head-on. Bliwise interviews people across the campus: from bus drivers and vaccine researchers to student activists, dining hall managers, and professors in areas from English to ecology. He explores the shift to teaching online and the reshaping of research programs; how surveillance testing and reconfiguring residence halls and dining sites helped limit the virus spread on campus; the efforts to promote student well-being and to sustain extracurricular programs; and what the surge in COVID-19 cases meant for the university health system. Bliwise also shows how broad cultural conversations surrounding the 2020 presidential election, climate change, free speech on campus, and systemic racism unfolded in this changed campus environment. Although the pandemic put remarkable pressures on the campus community, Bliwise demonstrates that it ultimately reaffirmed the importance of the campus experience in all its richness and complexity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-zNorth CarolinazDurham. 0aSchool management and organizationzNorth CarolinazDurham. 0aSocial distancing (Public health) and educationzNorth CarolinazDurham. 0aWeb-based instructionzNorth CarolinazDurham. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2022 Englishz978311099395008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2022z9783110994186oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023753?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023753/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMP